{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.03,0.65,0.09,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7899"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65699"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7899"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19254"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21923"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65699"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of increasing confusion, lethargy, and constipation. He has a history of squamous cell carcinoma of the lung diagnosed six months ago with known bone metastases. His medications include morphine and ondansetron. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is confused and dehydrated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory findings is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated alkaline phosphatase","Elevated serum albumin","Hypercalcaemia","Hypophosphataemia","Macrocytic anaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of hypercalcaemia of malignancy, including confusion, lethargy, constipation, and dehydration. Squamous cell carcinoma commonly causes hypercalcaemia through both direct osteolytic bone destruction and paraneoplastic effects via parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is present in up to 30% of patients with cancer, particularly those with bone metastases. The symptoms typically develop gradually and include confusion, lethargy, constipation, nausea, and polyuria leading to dehydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with squamous cell carcinoma. Cancer-related anaemia is usually normocytic and occurs due to chronic disease, bone marrow infiltration, or treatment effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated serum albumin\u003C/strong\u003E would be unusual in advanced cancer. Malignancy typically causes hypoalbuminaemia due to cachexia, inflammation, and poor nutritional status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypophosphataemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of malignancy-associated bone disease. In fact, bone metastases often cause elevated phosphate levels due to bone destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevated alkaline phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E can occur with bone metastases but is less specific than hypercalcaemia for this clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma with bone metastases commonly causes hypercalcaemia through osteolytic activity and paraneoplastic effects.","Cancer-related anaemia is typically normocytic, not macrocytic.","Malignancy typically causes hypoalbuminaemia due to cachexia and inflammatory effects."],"references":["Wang Y, Mukkamalla SKR, Singh R, Babiker HM, Lyons S. Esophageal Cancer. 2024 Aug 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083661","Codipilly DC, Wang KK. Squamous Cell Carcinoma of the Esophagus. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2022 Sep;51(3):457-484. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2022.06.005. Epub 2022 Aug 29. PMID: 36153105","Hadian Y, Howell JY, Ramsey ML, et al. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma. [Updated 2024 Jul 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441939/","Burton KA, Ashack KA, Khachemoune A. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma: A Review of High-Risk and Metastatic Disease. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2016 Oct;17(5):491-508. doi: 10.1007/s40257-016-0207-3. PMID: 27358187."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T17:31:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-26T17:31:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7899"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65699"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":